{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502404"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:43:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:43:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1854"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1854"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.29,0.31,0.19,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92821"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1854"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76186"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"3460"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1508"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13355"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31599"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42415"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44522"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92821"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with an eight-day history of being generally unwell, with fevers and persistent right upper quadrant pain. She has a medical history of myocardial infarction six weeks ago and takes aspirin, atorvastatin, metoprolol, and ramipril. She does not smoke and has no relevant family history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.4\u00b0C. There is a tender mass in the right upper quadrant with localised guarding. The remainder of the abdominal examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations are shown (Images 1-2). An ultrasound examination confirms the diagnosis of acute calculous cholecystitis, with a thickened gallbladder wall and pericholecystic fluid. She is started on intravenous fluids and antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue current management plan with ursodeoxycholic acid","Emergency laparoscopic cholecystectomy","Elective cholecystectomy","Percutaneous cholecystostomy","Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute calculous cholecystitis in the context of a recent myocardial infarction six weeks ago. The timing of this recent cardiac event significantly influences the management approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElective cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management plan for this patient. While early laparoscopic cholecystectomy is generally the standard of care for acute cholecystitis, the recent myocardial infarction represents a significant perioperative risk factor. Current guidelines recommend postponing elective surgery for at least 6-8 weeks (and ideally up to 6 months) after a myocardial infarction to reduce the risk of perioperative cardiac complications. The appropriate approach is to continue conservative management with antibiotics until the acute inflammation resolves, then plan for an elective cholecystectomy after an appropriate interval, with cardiology input regarding optimal timing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmergency laparoscopic cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would carry an unacceptably high cardiac risk given the patient\u0027s recent myocardial infarction. Additionally, the eight-day duration of symptoms and presence of a palpable inflammatory mass suggest advanced inflammation, which increases the likelihood of conversion to an open procedure and associated complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous cholecystostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a temporising procedure typically reserved for patients who are critically ill with sepsis, have failed conservative management, or are deemed too high-risk for surgery. While this patient has cardiac risk factors, she appears to be responding to conservative management and is not demonstrating signs of sepsis or gallbladder perforation that would necessitate this intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography\u003C/strong\u003E (ERCP) would be indicated if there were evidence of choledocholithiasis, cholangitis, or biliary obstruction. The patient\u0027s normal liver function tests and clinical presentation are not suggestive of common bile duct stones or obstruction, making ERCP unnecessary in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue current management plan with ursodeoxycholic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate. Ursodeoxycholic acid is used for dissolution of small cholesterol gallstones in select patients who are poor surgical candidates and have functioning gallbladders. It is not effective for acute cholecystitis management and would not address the underlying inflammatory process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Elective cholecystectomy is the preferred management for acute cholecystitis in patients with recent myocardial infarction, as immediate surgery carries significant cardiac risk.","Conservative management with antibiotics is appropriate for the initial treatment of acute cholecystitis when surgery must be delayed.","Cholecystectomy should generally be delayed for at least 6-8 weeks after a myocardial infarction to reduce perioperative cardiac risk."],"references":["Ibrahim M, Sarvepalli S, Morris-Stiff G, et al. Gallstones: Watch and wait, or intervene? Cleveland Cl J Med. 2018; 85: 323-31. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29634468/","Palsson SH, Engstrom C, Enochsson L, et al. Risk factors for postoperative myocardial infarct following cholecystectomy: a population-based study. HPB 2020, 22:34\u201340. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31327561/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76186"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1854"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14613"},{"type":"media","id":"14614"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14613"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a44f54f0-1e61-4166-a6c9-d29d22bc7183.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a44f54f0-1e61-4166-a6c9-d29d22bc7183.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":127}},{"type":"media","id":"14614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14614"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5abfe3f3-58ff-41c0-ba6d-28f7539b8bc9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5abfe3f3-58ff-41c0-ba6d-28f7539b8bc9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":305}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76186"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"